		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Charleston&#44; S. C.</placeName> <date>April 15. 5619</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Is. Leeser</addressee>&#44; <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">Dear Sir&#8212;</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Altho&#39; I have but<lb/> very little time before <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; yet&#44; anxious to have the <hi rend="underline">status</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">quo ante bellum</hi> restored before that holy day&#44; I will reply<lb/> at once&#44; even in but few lines.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Not accustomed to boast of what I do in the <sic>fulfilment</sic><lb/> of what I deem my duty&#44; I never told you&#44; that I <hi rend="underline">did</hi><lb/> write to <persName>Dr Philippson</persName> concerning your <sic>defence</sic> against the<lb/> slanderous attacks of the author of the &#8220;Tkizzin<add>&#63;</add>&#8221;&#44; and made<lb/> my commentary upon his &#40;<persName>Dr Ph&#39;s</persName>.&#41; silence.  But the Doctor<lb/> neither published my letter&#44; nor made even the slightest<lb/> mention of it in several of his epistles to me.  This man<lb/> one of the reasons why I broke off all official connection<lb/> with the Zeitung des Judenthums.  You may be assured&#44; I<lb/> spoke very plainly &#38; bluntly to him.  Nor did I stop there.<lb/>  In a letter to <persName>Stein&#39;s</persName> &#8220;<add>&#63;</add>&#8221; &#40;published in No 4&#44;<lb/> <date>1858</date>&#44; p. 135&#45;136&#41;&#44; I alluded to the injustice done us by the Z.d.J.&#44;<lb/> and stated that the author of the &#8220;Tkizzin&#44;&#8221; was nothing<lb/> less than &#8220;<add>&#63;</add><lb/> <add>&#63;</add>&#8221;&#59; but what was the consequence&#63;  <persName>Dr Ph.</persName><lb/> &#38; <persName>Mr. Eppstein</persName>&#44; now sojourning in <placeName>Breslaw</placeName>&#44; kept<lb/> silent&#44; and that was the last of that affair.  Could I<lb/> do more&#63;  It was my intention&#44; &#38; <persName>Stein</persName> knew it&#44; to get</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>either <persName>Dr P.</persName> or <persName>Mr. Eppstein</persName> into a controversy with me upon that<lb/> topic&#59; but they preferred to &#8220;<hi rend="underline">show no light</hi>.&#8221;  From all this you<lb/> must now perceive that I have &#8220;seconded you in your endeavor<lb/> to have justice done to you&#44;&#8221; &#38; trust you will now in justice to me <del>&#63;</del><lb/> reconsider your remark&#58; <del>but in</del> &#8220;in this too I<lb/> feel disappointed&#44;&#8221; as your conclusion was certainly an incor&#45;<lb/>rect one.  I do not blame you for it&#59; the fault lies in my<lb/> silence.  But I beg you&#44; once for all&#44; to be assured&#44; that I<lb/> am incapable of doing injustice to any one&#59; nothing can<lb/> mortify me more than to have injustice done to me&#44; &#38;&#44; therefore&#44;<lb/> I always act according to <persName>Hillel&#39;s</persName> maxim&#58; <add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">As I had ordered but <hi rend="underline">one</hi> Bible&#44; I kept one&#44; and<lb/> handed the other to <persName>Mr. Hart</persName> &#38; took his receipt for the<lb/> same.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">This must suffice for to&#45;day&#8212;<add>Hebrew</add> is<lb/> coming fast upon me&#44; so good <add>Hebrew</add>&#44; yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(11)"><persName role="author">Dr M Mayer</persName></p>
				<p>The little letter to <persName>Mr. Hart</persName><lb/> has been delivered.</p>
		</body>
